[normal]Can use of h[bold]eat from power generation through combined heat and power CHP reduce emissions for[bold] the power sector?[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]On the 24
[normal]th
[normal] or August we submitted a letter to Ed Davey
[normal] ref
[normal] copied to Tim Yeo Committee Chairman, Phillip Lowe Director General for Energy at the European Commission, Professor David Mackay, and Dr Fatih Birol Chief Economist and Director of the International Energy agency
[normal] expressing serious concerns about the 
[normal]ana
[normal]lytical methods used by the EU emission trading scheme EUETS adopted by the UK for Electricity Market Reform.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]A paper given to the International Association of Energy Economists which analyses EUETS, Dukes and CHPQA 
[normal]in detail was submitted with our
[normal] letter
[normal].
[normal] ref
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The formulas signal a reduction in powe
[normal]r emissions when 
[normal]waste heat is used.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The formulas 
[normal]assume that this, now useful, 
[normal]rejec
[normal]t heat has been generated in an
[normal] “imaginary” boiler.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The imaginary fuel for the boiler is then deducted from the actual fue
[normal]l being used for power generation to calculate lower emissions for electricity 
[normal]sector and their consumers
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The formula results in a 
[normal]serious 
[normal]“emissions” 
[normal]market distortion
[normal] 
[normal]contravening
[normal] 
[normal]the second law of thermody
[normal]na
[normal]mics.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]This method was at one time used for 
[normal]the UK statistics “Dukes” to calculate the fuel use
[normal] for electricity generation from 
[normal]Drax when 
[normal]some of the 
[normal]heat 
[normal]from condensing the steam that normally goes
[normal] to
[normal] the cooling towers, was 
[normal]diverted to grow tomatoes,
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Dukes retains elements of this methodology
[normal] with its allocation of  
[normal]any 
[normal]benefit from CHP two thirds to the heat and one third to the electricity
[normal]. I
[normal]n practice no benefit
[normal] arises for power production and 
[normal]electricity consumers.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Dukes statistics 
[normal]are used as 
[normal]input to other policy models such as Markal/T
[normal]imes used by DECC
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]T
[normal]he Markal output 
[normal]may be 
[normal]flaw
[normal]ed if the input is flawed. 
[normal] .
