[normal]The EU Carnot method for analysing Renewable CHP.[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]Page 16 to 18 Ref 2 explain 
[normal]how 
[normal]the 
[normal]EU Carnot 
[normal]“Exergy” 
[normal]method for 
[normal]the analysis of renewable CHP disadvantages low temperature district heating by assuming it operates at 150C.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]We 
[normal]further 
[normal]identify an error in th
[normal]e
[normal] formula as when it allocates emissions the 
[normal]total emissions after allocatio
[normal]n are greater than the 
[normal]actual 
[normal]emissions from the fuel input to the CHP.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Analysis of the fo[bold]rmula for the EU CHP directive and thermodynamic superiority of heat from CHP compared to heat from electric heat pumps.[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]We analyse t
[normal]he EU directive which was formulated on the basis that CHP reduced electricity sector emissions hence the idea of good quality electricity from CHP and an incentive on the electricity production not the heat ill
[normal]ustrated in the following chart on Page 34 Re
[normal]f 2                                       
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Note the actual primary energy savings for the heat sector are illustrated by the red triangles.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The EU directive signals 
[normal]the savings by the blue line a combination of two different products where there are 
[normal]not savings in the electricity sector only savings in the heat sector with the blue line showing the overall saving for the combined sectors.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Reject heat from electricity generation is a major energy resource always at a higher temperature than the enviro
[normal]nment for its rejection in line with the second law.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]This reject heat exceeds UK domestic gas 
[normal]energy supply in quantity but 
[normal]not in quality and exergy.
[normal] Exergy allows the fundamental relative “value” of power and heat to be assessed and is an important conc
[normal]ept for optimal use of scarce fuel resources.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]CHP, a “Virtual heat pump” (ref 
[normal] &amp; ref 
[normal]) , can in practice decarbonize dwellings heated by gas retrofitted as at Odense in Denmark to the coal fired CHP and district heat 
[normal]where ten units of waste heat are up
[normal]graded using one unit of electricity.  The ten is directly
[normal] comparable to coefficients of 
[normal]performance for air source electric heat pumps of two to four driven by the plants electricity.
