[normal]Effect of [bold]Real Rate[bold]s[bold] of Ret[bold]urn and lifetime assumptions on output from [bold]models.[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]We note
[normal] 
[normal]Ricardo-AEA use a 15% real rate of return for information feeding into the DECC Monte Carlo model.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]We have noted Delta Energy use
[normal] a 10% real rate of return to evaluate the heat infrastructure in their work for the Energy Networks Association and National Grid.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Whilst one can identify anomalies in outputs from models
[normal] such as a saving in the electricity sector with CHP or cost of he
[normal]at from CHP heat network to consumers higher than cost of heat from gas boilers Delta Energy. One 
[normal]cannot
[normal] g
[normal]ain access to 
[normal]model to 
[normal]check the assumptions that determine
[normal] the results
[normal].
[normal] 
[normal]Or 
[normal]whether the modeller has cross subsidised electricity consumers from heat 
[normal]consumers.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]To indicate how easy it can be to change the output of a model by changing lifetime and real rates of return the following table
[normal] illustrates the effect by presenting the information in the form of an equivalent payback on the investment
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]We w
[normal]ould as an example expect a low temperature heat network to have a lifetime of over 100 years and be assessed at the same rate of return as other infrastructure investments such as incremental insulation or investment in extension of gas and electricity in
[normal]frastructure or storage, funded by consumers.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]One can see that the 
[normal]Ricardo-AEA
[normal] 15% assumption will require the heat network to pay back with a lifetime of 60 years in 6.67 years for low CO2 heat supply.
[normal]For an insulation measure with a 60 year life 
[normal]evaluated at 3.5% for inclusion as a building regulation measure
[normal] 
[normal]the payback is 24.94 years.
[normal]The Delta Energy assumption of 10% requires a 9.97 year pay back on the heat network and a 7.6 year payback every time a new gas boiler is installed at the end of 
[normal]its 15 year lifetime.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Currently it appears 
[normal]different models make different assumptions
[normal]. 
[normal] 
[normal]W
[normal]e have concentrated in this evidence on modelling areas where the boiler displacement 
[normal]method is 
[normal]used
[normal] by modellers and the EU.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The Pathways modelling by DECC 
[normal]uses the correct power plant displacement method with an assumption of COP of 7 for heat from CHP and we note that the latest CIBSE guide AM12 also endorses this method of analysis.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]We recommend that any modelling of the energy sector has a clear list of 
[normal]costs and lifetimes for the elements that are modelled and where the model is dealing with CHP and its joint products a clear example of how the respective fuel and CO2 overheads for the two products have been calculated in the model.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The [bold]domestic sector [bold]heat load. The [bold]Low CO[bold]2 heat supply investment [bold]option [bold]networks[bold] to [bold]decarbonize domestic sector compared to [bold]investment in incremental fabric insulation.[bold] Low CO2 piped heat supply first better than fabric first due to large savings[bold]?[bold]&#xa0;[bold]Heat networks are the most
[normal] common form of heat supply in the UK where water is the vehicle for carrying the heat from its source to its destination mainly to perform three heating functions. One to provide domestic hot water, two to heat the air we breathe the ventilation heat load
[normal], three to counteract heat loss through the fabric of the building the “fabric load”.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Often the importance of the domestic hot water and ventilation loads are forgotten as well as the electric loads for dishwashing and laundry that can be met either from 
[normal]district heat or electricity.
