[normal]The 
[normal]detailed spreadsheet has been supplied to the committee to illustrate why the low carbon heat sup
[normal]ply option offers such 
[normal]high savings compared to fabric insulation.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The relative impact of low CO2 heat supply and demand side measures is illustrated in a pap
[normal]er to the solar trade association
[normal] and its poster
[normal] as well as results illustrated below from a retrofit for the future project.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]In our paper we 
[normal]propose Modular Energy Hubs incorporating 500 kW-2000kW CHP, heat pumps, fuel and heat stores, with battery sto
[normal]rage and exchange for Electric Vehicles. The Hubs optimize intermittent renewable electricity from wind and solar PV, minimizing electrical infrastructure investment for 2050.  Large scale solar thermal feeds the 75C flow 30C return heat networks.
[normal] The conc
[normal]ept has been discussed with Greg Barker and we understand it will be modelled by DECC.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]We suggest that when heat from fossil CHP has a lower CO2 footprint 
[normal]i.e.
[normal] higher COP than electric heat pumps it should be treated as qualifying for the same incentives as heat from 
[normal]“renewab
[normal]le” biomass and 
[normal]electric he
[normal]at pumps’
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The paper submitted to Ed Davey explains that electric heat pumps 
[normal]can 
[normal]generate higher CO
[normal]2
[normal] emissions t
[normal]han fossil CHP, where electricity for the heat pump is fossil-derived.
[normal] 
[normal]Also CO2 emissions when wood is burnt on a grate are larger than emissions from coal.  
[normal]Whilst the sustainable element associated with the wood has to be considered current regulations b
[normal]y treating its emissions as zero independent 
[normal]of the
[normal] efficiency of the conversion of the wood to energy resulting in poor use of a scarce resource.  
